---
import ElevationLayout from '../../layouts/ElevationLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../../components/elevation/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../../components/elevation/Section.astro';
import { getProductBySlug } from '../../lib/products/registry';
import { productJsonLd } from '../../lib/structured-data';

const product = getProductBySlug('agent-memory-architecture-guide')!;
const jsonLd = productJsonLd(product, 'https://evoked.dev/products/agent-memory-architecture-guide');
---

<ElevationLayout
  title="Agent Memory Architecture Guide"
  description="Design what your agents remember, what they forget, and who decides. Memory types, governance, session protocols, and retention policy. $49 PDF."
  structuredData={jsonLd}
>
  <Hero
    eyebrowParts={["Products", "Context engineering"]}
    headline="What should your agent remember - and who decides?"
    metaphor={["Memory is not storage. Memory is identity."]}
    sub="Memory types, governance, retention, and the canonical rule for when memories conflict."
  />

  <Section marker="FIG · I" heading="Why memory is governance">
    <p class="lede">
      Memory is not storage. Memory is identity. What your agent remembers
      shapes who it becomes - and what it forgets determines what it can never
      be. Most agent systems treat memory as a technical problem. It's a
      governance problem.
    </p>
    <p class="pd-body">
      This guide gives you the framework for designing memory that serves
      people - including the right to be forgotten.
    </p>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · II" heading="What you get">
    <div class="pd-features">
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Memory type taxonomy</h3>
        <p>Operational memory, identity memory, relationship memory, and decision memory. Each type has different governance needs. Treating them the same is the first design mistake.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Memory governance framework</h3>
        <p>Who can write, read, modify, and delete each type of memory. Authority without governance is just access control. Governance without authority is just policy.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>The canonical rule</h3>
        <p>One sentence that defines which memory source wins when memories conflict. The most important sentence in your entire memory architecture.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-feature">
        <h3>Retention policy</h3>
        <p>What stays, what expires, and what must be deletable on request. Includes the right to be forgotten - not as compliance, but as sovereignty.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · III" heading="What's inside">
    <div class="pd-pillars">
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">1</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Memory types</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"What kinds of memory does your agent hold - and are you treating them all the same?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">2</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Memory governance</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"Who has authority over each memory type - and what constrains that authority?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">3</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Session protocols</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"How does memory persist across sessions without accumulating drift?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">4</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>The canonical rule</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"When two memory sources disagree, which one wins - and why?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-pillar">
        <span class="pd-pillar-number">5</span>
        <div class="pd-pillar-body">
          <h3>Retention and forgetting</h3>
          <p class="pd-pillar-question">"What is the right to be forgotten - and does your architecture honor it?"</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · IV" heading="Who this is for">
    <div class="pd-audience">
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>AI developers</h3>
        <p>Building agents with persistent memory. The architecture decisions you make now determine whether memory serves the user or surveils them.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Privacy engineers</h3>
        <p>Agent memory creates new categories of personal data. This framework gives you governance that maps to privacy principles, not just compliance checkboxes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pd-audience-card">
        <h3>Product teams</h3>
        <p>Your agents remember things about your users. The question is whether you've designed that memory with the user's sovereignty in mind - or only your feature roadmap.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="FIG · V" heading="Buy the guide">
    <div class="pd-purchase">
      <div class="pd-price">$49</div>
      <p class="pd-purchase-lead">PDF download. Design memory for as many agent systems as you need.</p>
      <a
        href={product.stripePaymentLink}
        class="pd-buy-cta"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
      >Buy the Guide</a>
      <p class="pd-purchase-fineprint">
        Includes the memory type taxonomy, governance framework, session
        protocols, canonical rule template, retention policy, and 10-minute
        memory diagnostic.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section marker="NOTA · BENE" heading="Go deeper" closing={true}>
    <p class="lede">
      The guide gives you the memory architecture. If you want the full trust
      framework around it, two doorways from here.
    </p>
    <div class="pd-upsell">
      <a href="/products/trust-architecture-blueprint" class="pd-upsell-card">
        <h3>Trust Architecture Blueprint</h3>
        <p>Memory is one of four pillars. The Blueprint shows how identity, memory, governance, and refusal rights work together. $49.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">See the Blueprint &rarr;</span>
      </a>
      <a href="https://cal.com/cal.com-evoked/discovery-call" class="pd-upsell-card" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <h3>Discovery call</h3>
        <p>Free 30-minute call to discuss your memory architecture and figure out next steps.</p>
        <span class="pd-upsell-link">Schedule &rarr;</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </Section>
</ElevationLayout>
